PART 2 Feature Engineering¶

we have features related to:

  • Numberical Data
  1. Age
  2. Dependents
  3. Average Loan Amount
  4. Total Loans
  5. Loan Duration (We tend to not use these kind of variables , as it can be handle with Policy Rules for the sake of exercise considering this variable)
  • Application data
  1. Marital Status
  2. Job Type
  3. Job Industry
  4. Loan Purpose
  5. Adresss_province

Before Proceed to Modeling, it is very important to fine tune your variables that will help us later to improve model performance. fine tuning includes adjustment of outliers, replacement of NaN or negative values.

One thing to make sure here is your coarse classing should follow business rules of the product.

In [ ]:
# Drop rows where 'GBFlag_cus' column has NaN values

Variance Threshold¶

Variance Threshold is a feature selector that removes all the low variance features from the dataset that are of no great use in modeling. It looks only at the features (x), not the desired outputs/target (y), and can thus be used for unsupervised learning.

  • High Variance in predictors: Good Indication
  • Low Variance predictors: Not good for model We can drop constant features using Sklearn’s Variance Threshold. Default Value of Threshold is 0
-  If Variance Threshold = 0 (Remove Constant Features )
-  If Variance Threshold > 0 (Remove Quasi-Constant Features )
  • Constant Feature: Same value in all the records.
  • Quasi Constant Feature: One of the values is dominant 99.9%.
In [ ]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import VarianceThreshold

data_universe_num = df.select_dtypes(include = 'number')
print('data_universe_num', data_universe_num.shape)

In [ ]:
# Check for zero variance or degenerate variables and drop them i.e if a variable has variance less than the threshold 
# drop them otherwise keep them 

## Specify variance of 10%
near_zero = VarianceThreshold(threshold = 0.10)
near_zero.fit_transform(data_universe_num)

# Get column index of the variable with variance > 10%
highvar = near_zero.get_support(indices=True)

### Get columns in a list
variance_relevant_variables = data_universe_num.columns[highvar].tolist()

# Zero variance variables
zero_variance_variables = [col for col in data_universe_num.columns.tolist() if col not in variance_relevant_variables]

print('variance_relevant_variables', len(variance_relevant_variables))
print('zero_variance_variables', len(zero_variance_variables))

variance_relevant_variables 19
zero_variance_variables 0

Fortunately, we have no variables with zero variance so we are not dropping any variables now

1.Fine Classing & Coarse Classing¶

For Application Variables we will try to bin them with respect to their nature.

Conventionally, we only try to manage 4/5 bins at max. Reason is more the bins the more your model is going to complex that will relate to overfitting eventually. lesser bins like 1/2 we need to avoid so model should not oversimplify

In [ ]:
# Regroup Educational status
df['loan_purpose_binned'] = np.where(df['loan_purpose'].isin(['Buying electronics', 'Buying a vehicle', 'Home renovation', 'Online shopping']), 'LifeStyle Expenses', 
    np.where(df['loan_purpose'].isin(['Paying other debts', 'Miscellaneous']), 'Other Expenses', 
    np.where(df['loan_purpose'].isin(['Daily necessities', 'Educational expenses']), 'Running Expenses',
    np.where(df['loan_purpose'].isin(['Business capital', 'Holiday expenses / Umrah', 'Transfer to Family/Friends']), 'Investment/Payment Expenses', 
    np.where(df['loan_purpose'].isin(['Healthcare costs	']), 'Health Expenses', df['loan_purpose'])))))

    'sales / marketing': 'Business and Finance',
    'administration / finance / hr': 'Business and Finance',
    'banking': 'Business and Finance',
    'technical / computer': 'Technical and Infrastructure',
    'construction / real estate': 'Technical and Infrastructure',
    'factory / warehouse': 'Technical and Infrastructure',
    'service': 'Service and Hospitality',
    'hospitality': 'Service and Hospitality',
    'entertainment / event': 'Service and Hospitality',
    'education': 'Health and Education',
    'health': 'Health and Education',
    'body care': 'Health and Education',
    'design / art': 'Creative and Legal',
    'law / security / politics': 'Creative and Legal',
    # Assigning these specific sectors and nan values to 'Other Industry'
    'transportation': 'Other Industry',
    'domestic staff': 'Other Industry'
}

# Apply the binning and handle missing values
df['job_industry_binned'] = df['job_industry'].map(sector_bins).fillna('Other Industry')

# Clean 'dependent' data: replace negative values with 0 and NaN values with -999
df['dependent'] = df['dependent'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x < 0 else x)
df['dependent'].fillna(-999, inplace=True)
In [ ]:
# Clean 'dependent' data: replace negative values with 0 and NaN values with -999
df['dependent'] = df['dependent'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x < 0 else x)
df['dependent'].fillna(-999, inplace=True)

# Separate -999 values into a distinct category directly within the 'Dependent_Bin' column
df['Dependent_Bin'] = pd.cut(df['dependent'], bins=[-1000, -998, 0, 1, 2, 5], labels=['Missing', '0', '1', '2', '3-5'], right=False)

The visualizations of various features in relation to the GBFlag_cus (indicating whether customers are considered "Good" or "Bad") reveal several key insights that can help the business understand where bad customers are mainly coming from and identify potential risk factors. Let's discuss the insights derived from each of the visualized features:

1. Loan Purpose¶

  • Certain loan purposes may have higher proportions of bad customers. If specific categories, like "Running Expenses" or "Investment/Payment Expenses", showed a notably higher ratio of bad customers, it suggests these loan purposes could be riskier. Such patterns can guide risk assessment and loan approval strategies.

2. Address (Province)¶

  • The distribution across provinces indicates that some regions may have a higher incidence of bad customers. If regions like "Jakarta (Special Region)" or "West Java" displayed a higher concentration of bad customers, it suggests geographical factors or economic conditions in those areas might influence default rates. This can inform geographic targeting and risk mitigation efforts.

3. Job Industry¶

  • The job industry of borrowers also shows variation in the proportion of good and bad customers. Industries that appear more frequently among bad customers could indicate sectors with less stable income, influencing loan repayment capabilities. This insight can be used for employment verification and loan approval processes.

4. Age¶

  • Age distribution suggests age groups from 22 to 34 might be more prone to being classified as bad customers. For example, if younger or older age bins show a higher ratio of bad customers, it might reflect different risk profiles based on life stage, financial stability, and credit experience.

5. Dependent Count¶

  • The number of dependents appears to influence the likelihood of being a bad customer. A higher number of dependents could correlate with increased financial pressure, affecting loan repayment. Identifying specific dependent counts that correlate strongly with bad customers can help refine loan eligibility criteria.

6. Average Loan Amount¶

  • The analysis of average loan amounts by customer type might reveal whether larger or smaller loans are more likely to be associated with bad customers. This could relate to the borrower's financial capability to manage debt.

7. Average Total Loans¶

  • The number of loans taken by a customer and their risk classification suggests that customers with a higher number of loans might be at a higher risk of default. This insight is crucial for assessing a customer's debt burden and financial health.

8. Loan Duration¶

  • Loan duration preferences between good and bad customers can indicate risk preferences or financial planning capabilities. Shorter or longer durations might be associated with different risk profiles, affecting default rates.

Specific Insights on High-Risk Segments:

  • However, the business can use these insights to focus on loan purposes, industries, age groups, and other factors that show a higher proportion of bad customers for more detailed analysis. Identifying these patterns helps in refining underwriting criteria, setting targeted risk mitigation strategies, and potentially customizing product offerings to better manage and distribute risk across the portfolio.

By focusing on these insights, the business can more effectively identify and manage potential risks associated with loan approvals, contributing to a more robust and resilient financial strategy.

Calculate WOE and IV¶

Weight of Evidence (WOE) and Information Value (IV) are key metrics in the development of credit scoring models, and their importance is especially pronounced in the realm of financial services, including banking and credit risk assessment. Here's why they are so crucial for feature engineering in this context:

Weight of Evidence (WOE)¶

  1. Transforms Variables: WOE provides a method to transform categorical variables into a continuous measure, making it easier to include them in models that require numerical input, such as logistic regression.

  2. Handles Missing Values: It offers a straightforward approach to deal with missing values, allowing for the incorporation of missingness as a separate category, if appropriate.

  3. Ensures Monotonic Relationship: By using WOE, one can ensure a monotonic relationship between the independent variables and the log odds of the dependent variable, enhancing model performance and interpretability.

  4. Risk Differentiation: It helps in differentiating the risk by assigning higher WOE values to categories that indicate higher risk, making it a natural fit for credit scoring models where risk assessment is key.

Information Value (IV)¶

  1. Feature Selection: IV is an excellent tool for feature selection. It quantifies the predictive power of an independent variable in relation to the dependent variable. In credit scoring models, this helps in selecting the most relevant variables for predicting default risk.

  2. Assesses Predictive Power: IV values range from 0 to infinity, with higher values indicating stronger predictive power. This allows modelers to rank variables by their importance in predicting the outcome.

  3. Reduces Overfitting: By selecting only the variables with significant IV, you reduce the risk of overfitting your model with irrelevant or weak predictors.

  4. Simplicity and Efficiency: IV calculation is straightforward and does not require building a model to assess the predictive power of a variable. This makes the feature selection process both efficient and effective.

Practical Implementation in Credit Scoring¶

In the context of credit scoring, WOE and IV are instrumental in developing robust models that accurately predict the likelihood of a borrower defaulting on a loan. These methods allow financial institutions to make informed decisions, manage risk effectively, and ensure regulatory compliance by providing clear, interpretable metrics for model development and variable selection.Overall, WOE and IV enhance the predictiveness and interpretability of credit scoring models, making them indispensable tools in the feature engineering phase of model development.

import pandas as pd

def calculate_woe_and_iv_for_all_features(df_train, df_test, features, target):
    woe_results = {}
    iv_summary = {'Feature': [], 'Train IV': [], 'Test IV': []}

    for feature in features:
        # Assuming woe_cat now returns a tuple of (DataFrame, IV value)
        woe_df_train, iv_train = woe_cat(df_train, feature, target)
        woe_df_test, iv_test = woe_cat(df_test, feature, target)
        plot_by_woe(woe_df_train, feature)
        plot_by_woe(woe_df_test, feature)


        # Combine Train and Test DataFrames with a spacer
        spacer_df = pd.DataFrame({(' ', ' ', f'Spacer_{i}'): [None] * len(woe_df_train) for i in range(1, 4)})
        woe_combined = pd.concat([woe_df_train, spacer_df, woe_df_test], axis=1)
        woe_results[feature] = woe_combined

        # Append IV values to the summary
        iv_summary['Feature'].append(feature)
        iv_summary['Train IV'].append(iv_train)
        iv_summary['Test IV'].append(iv_test)

    return woe_results, pd.DataFrame(iv_summary)

# Assuming df_train and df_test are your Train and Test datasets
features = ['loan_purpose_binned', 'address_provinsi_binned', 'marital_status', 'job_type', 'job_industry_binned',
            'Age_binned', 'Dependent_Bin', 'Avg_Loan_Amount_binned', 'Avg_total_loans_binned', 'loan_duration_binned']
target = 'GBFlag_cus'

# Calculate WoE for each feature for both Train and Test datasets and store the results
woe_results, iv_summary_df = calculate_woe_and_iv_for_all_features(Train, Test, features, target)

with pd.ExcelWriter('Characteristics_analysis_report.xlsx', engine="openpyxl") as writer:
    # Write each feature's WOE table to its sheet
    for variable_name, data in woe_results.items():
        data.to_excel(writer, sheet_name=variable_name, startrow=1)
    
    # Write the summary sheet
    iv_summary_df.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Summary', index=False)

Characteristic Analysis or CA Report¶

At this stage of the modeling, we compile CA report in which all the features alongiwth their respective WOE and IV for train and test present.

The variable selection happen on the basis of this criteria.

  1. Information Value range: 0.02>x<0.5
  2. Population Stablity Index: <0.2
  3. Variance Inflation Factor: <5

Calculation of PSI and VIF is necessary before proceed for Modeling. The Process is to make sure the variables we will consider for modeling will be of strongest predictor.

In this exercise, we have only calculated Woe and IV to proceed.

from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold, cross_validate
from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score, roc_curve, auc, confusion_matrix
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from catboost import CatBoostClassifier
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
from lightgbm import LGBMClassifier
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

# Define custom scoring function for Gini coefficient
def gini_score(y_true, y_pred):
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_true, y_pred)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
    gini_coefficient = 2 * roc_auc - 1
    return gini_coefficient

# Create Stratified K-fold cross-validation
cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, random_state=1, shuffle=True)

# Define scoring metrics
scoring = {
    'f1': make_scorer(f1_score),
    'precision': make_scorer(precision_score),
    'recall': make_scorer(recall_score),
    'auc-roc': make_scorer(roc_auc_score),
    'gini': make_scorer(gini_score)
}

# Initialize models
models = {
    'Random Forest': RandomForestClassifier(),
    'Decision Tree': DecisionTreeClassifier(),
    'Logistic Regression': LogisticRegression(),
    'CatBoost': CatBoostClassifier(),
    'XGBoost': XGBClassifier(),
    'LightGBM': LGBMClassifier()
}

# Initialize results dictionary
results = {'Model': [], 'F1-score': [], 'Precision': [], 'Recall': [], 'AUC-ROC': [], 'Gini': []}

# Evaluate each model
for model_name, model in models.items():
    scores = cross_validate(model, X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring, cv=cv)
    results['Model'].append(model_name)
    results['F1-score'].append(np.mean(scores['test_f1']))
    results['Precision'].append(np.mean(scores['test_precision']))
    results['Recall'].append(np.mean(scores['test_recall']))
    results['AUC-ROC'].append(np.mean(scores['test_auc-roc']))
    results['Gini'].append(np.mean(scores['test_gini']))

# Create results DataFrame
results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)

# Display results
results_df

result = model.fit()

## Get Model Predictions

test_pred = result.predict(X_test_sm)

Test_Gini, Train_Gini = compute_gini(y_test, y_train, test_pred, train_pred)
display(result.summary2())

print('Model AIC:', round(result.aic, 3)) 
print('Model Train Gini:', round(Train_Gini, 3))
print('Model Test Gini:', round(Test_Gini, 3))

print("Diff: ", (Train_Gini - Test_Gini)/Train_Gini)

In [ ]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc, roc_auc_score
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, accuracy_score

# Calculate AUC-ROC
auc_roc_train = roc_auc_score(y_train, train_pred)
auc_roc_test = roc_auc_score(y_test, test_pred)

# Plot ROC curves for both training and testing sets
fpr_train, tpr_train, _ = roc_curve(y_train, train_pred)
fpr_test, tpr_test, _ = roc_curve(y_test, test_pred)

# Calculate Gini
gini = 2 * auc_roc_test - 1

# Convert predicted probabilities to binary predictions
y_pred = np.round(test_pred)

# Confusion Matrix
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

# Accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)

# Calculate KS (Kolmogorov-Smirnov) statistic
ks = max(tpr_test - fpr_test)

# Display the results
print(f"AUC-ROC: {auc_roc_test}")
print(f"Gini: {gini}")
print("Confusion Matrix:")
print(conf_matrix)
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy}")
print(f"KS: {ks}")

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(fpr_train, tpr_train, color='blue', lw=2, label='Train ROC curve' )
plt.plot(fpr_test, tpr_test, color='darkorange', lw=2, label='Test ROC curve')
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate', fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate', fontweight='bold')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve', fontweight='bold')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

import seaborn as sns 
# Create confusion matrix
# Create confusion matrix
# Create confusion matrix
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

# Calculate recall rates
recall_0 = conf_matrix[0, 0] / (conf_matrix[0, 0] + conf_matrix[0, 1])
recall_1 = conf_matrix[1, 1] / (conf_matrix[1, 0] + conf_matrix[1, 1])

# Set font size for heatmap
sns.set(font_scale=1.2)  # Adjust the value as needed

# Plot the confusion matrix using a heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
ax = sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False,
                 xticklabels=['Predicted 0', 'Predicted 1'],
                 yticklabels=['Actual 0', 'Actual 1'],
                 annot_kws={"size": 12, "weight": "bold"})  # Adjust size and weight as needed

# Add recall rates as text annotations
plt.text(0, -0.2, f'Recall 0: {recall_0:.2f}', ha='center', va='center', color='red', fontweight='bold', fontsize=12)
plt.text(1, -0.2, f'Recall 1: {recall_1:.2f}', ha='center', va='center', color='red', fontweight='bold', fontsize=12)

plt.xlabel('Predicted', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Actual', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.show()

Which metrics do you use? and why?¶

In Credit Scoring , we use Gini Coefficent as a Bench mark metric to check how is model performing on test. Any Gini above 25% is good to have in corporate environment. With a Real time Data, Gini above 35% basically means your model is discrimating Good and Bad Customers decently.

Later on, Quaterly Monitoring of Scorecard Involves Gini and AUC Roc Shift. If Gini goes below 25% means model needs redevelopment.

Explain why your model can be considered as good enough.¶

A Model consider to be good enough if the discrimation of GOOD and BAD customer is decent enough. Gini Coefficeint gives us the benchmark to check that and image shows logistic regression is the best one to use among the rest.

How can the business use the model?¶

Business can use the Model Predictions i.e. Probablity of Default to Accept or Reject Customer at the time of Application but setting up a scorecard threhold. For Business we develop a Cutoff Strategy Report to check Profit/Loss and Cummulative Bad Rates and different Scorecard Scales.

In [ ]:
# Calculate KS (Kolmogorov-Smirnov) statistic for each point on the ROC curve
ks_values = tpr_test - fpr_test

# Find the index corresponding to the maximum KS value
max_ks_index = np.argmax(ks_values)

# Plot the KS curve
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(fpr_test, ks_values, color='green', lw=2, label='KS Curve (max KS = {:.2f} at {:.2f})'.format(ks_values[max_ks_index], fpr_test[max_ks_index]))
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate', fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('KS Value', fontweight='bold')
plt.title('KS Curve', fontweight='bold')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

Risk Analysis¶

If the business would like to achieve 2% cumulative default rate, which loans should we accept?**¶

The analysis indicates that to achieve a 2% cumulative default rate, loans with a Probability of Default (PD) score of 96 or lower should be considered for acceptance. This threshold is highlighted in the plot, where the cumulative default rate line crosses the 2% marker, and is visualized by the green vertical line.

This threshold helps in making precise, data-driven decisions on which loans to approve, targeting a conservative default rate that minimizes risk while potentially excluding higher-risk loans.

In [ ]:
# Create a flag indicating default (1 for Bad customers, 0 for Good customers)
model_cutoff['default_flag'] = (model_cutoff['GBFlag_cus'] == 'Bad').astype(int)

# Sort data by PD score
data_sorted = model_cutoff.sort_values('PD')

# Calculate cumulative default rate
data_sorted['cumulative_defaults'] = data_sorted['default_flag'].cumsum()
data_sorted['cumulative_total'] = range(1, len(data_sorted) + 1)
data_sorted['cumulative_default_rate'] = data_sorted['cumulative_defaults'] / data_sorted['cumulative_total']

# Identify the maximum PD score for a 2% cumulative default rate
max_pd_for_2_percent_default = data_sorted[data_sorted['cumulative_default_rate'] <= 0.02]['PD'].max()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(data_sorted['PD'], data_sorted['cumulative_default_rate'], label='Cumulative Default Rate')
plt.axhline(y=0.02, color='r', linestyle='--', label='2% Default Rate')
plt.axvline(x=max_pd_for_2_percent_default, color='g', linestyle='--', label=f'PD Threshold: {max_pd_for_2_percent_default}')

plt.title('Cumulative Default Rate vs. Probability of Default (PD)')
plt.xlabel('Probability of Default (PD)')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Default Rate')
plt.legend()

plt.show()

# Visualize the correlation matrix
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f")
plt.title('Correlation Matrix: Features vs Default Flag')
plt.show()

What are the characteristics of a defaulter, and how important are they?¶

Based on the correlation analysis and the distribution of PD scores:

The PD score stands out as the most critical characteristic in predicting whether a customer is likely to default. Higher PD scores are strongly associated with a greater likelihood of default.

Most of the Loans taken by customers from Jawa Barat Province, Married, Age 30 with No Dependents and have taken 2 loans atleast.

Financial metrics like loan amount and recovered amount have some relationship with default risk but are not as predictive as the PD score. This suggests that while the size and recovery of a loan matter, the customer's probability of default score is a more direct measure of risk.

For businesses looking to minimize default risk, focusing on PD scores as a primary criterion for loan approval is a data-driven strategy. However, it's also essential to consider the full financial context, including loan amounts, recovery efforts, and the cost of issuing loans, as these factors collectively influence the overall risk and profitability of loan portfolios.

To further refine risk management strategies, businesses could explore additional variables (if available) or develop more sophisticated models that incorporate a broader range of predictive factors, including customer demographics, credit history, and economic conditions

Profit/Loss Analysis¶

Lets look at deeply where the profit with respect to Default rates. it will help business and product to identify where to apply cap to maintain disbursment and mitigate risk at the same time

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd

def cut_off_strat(data):
    temp_dict = {}
    
    df = pd.crosstab(data['PD_Binned'], data['GBFlag_cus'])
    df['Total'] = df.sum(axis=1)
    df['Bad.Rates'] = df['Bad']/df['Total']
    df['Cumulative.Default.Rate'] = df['Bad.Rates'].cumsum()  # Calculate cumulative default rate
    df['GBOdds'] = df['Good']/df['Bad']
    
    for PD in df.index:
        Disbs = data[data['PD_Binned']==PD]['loan_amount'].sum().astype(int)
        Disbs_Good = data[(data['PD_Binned']==PD) & (data['GBFlag_cus']=='Good')]['loan_amount'].sum().astype(int)
        Disbs_Bad = data[(data['PD_Binned']==PD) & (data['GBFlag_cus']=='Bad')]['loan_amount'].sum().astype(int)
        Repayments = data[data['PD_Binned']==PD]['recovered_amount'].sum().astype(int)
        Repayments_Good = data[(data['PD_Binned']==PD) & (data['GBFlag_cus']=='Good')]['recovered_amount'].sum().astype(int)
        Repayments_Bad = data[(data['PD_Binned']==PD) & (data['GBFlag_cus']=='Bad')]['recovered_amount'].sum().astype(int)
        Variable_Cost = data[data['PD_Binned']==PD]['Variable Cost'].sum().astype(int)
        Profit = data[data['PD_Binned']==PD]['Profit/Loss'].sum().astype(int)
        Mean_Profit = data[data['PD_Binned']==PD]['Profit/Loss'].mean()
        
        temp_dict.setdefault('Disbursements',[]).append(Disbs)
        temp_dict.setdefault('Disb.Good',[]).append(Disbs_Good)
        temp_dict.setdefault('Disb.Bad',[]).append(Disbs_Bad)
        temp_dict.setdefault('Repayments',[]).append(Repayments)
        temp_dict.setdefault('Repay.Good',[]).append(Repayments_Good)
        temp_dict.setdefault('Repay.Bad',[]).append(Repayments_Bad)
        temp_dict.setdefault('Variable.Cost',[]).append(Variable_Cost)
        temp_dict.setdefault('Profit/Loss',[]).append(Profit)
        temp_dict.setdefault('Profit(Without Cost)',[]).append(Repayments - Disbs)
        temp_dict.setdefault('Mean.Profit',[]).append(Mean_Profit)
        # temp_dict.setdefault('PSI count',[]).append(pssi)
    
    for k, v in temp_dict.items():
        df[k] = v
    
    df['Mean.Profit(Without Cost)'] = df['Profit(Without Cost)']/df['Total']
    
    return df


strategy =cut_off_strat(model_cutoff)

fig = go.Figure()

                         name='Variable Cost',
                         mode='lines+markers',
                         line=dict(color='blue'),  # Set line color
                         ))

                         name='Mean Profit (Without Cost)',
                         mode='lines+markers',
                         line=dict(color='red'),  # Set line color
                         yaxis='y2'  # Assign to secondary y-axis
                         ))

    xaxis=dict(title='PD Bin'),
    yaxis=dict(title='Variable Cost', titlefont=dict(color='blue'), tickfont=dict(color='blue')),

)
